# Added a function to check for dataset outliers, determined if the feature variables have values outside the bounds of the lower
# and upper quantile, with the Inter Quantile Range IQR included
def check_outliers(data):
    outliers = {}
    numeric_columns = data.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']).columns
    for column in numeric_columns:
        Q1 = data[column].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = data[column].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
        

        outlier_count = data[(data[column] < lower_bound) | (data[column] > upper_bound)].shape[0]
        outliers[column] = outlier_count
    return outliers

# The outliers are then checked per feature
outlier_counts = check_outliers(data)
print("Outliers per feature:")
print(outlier_counts)

# Added a function that removes the outliers lying outside of the lower and upper bound of the respective lower and upper quartile scores
def remove_outliers(data, columns):
    for column in columns:
        Q1 = data[column].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = data[column].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
        
       
        data = data[(data[column] >= lower_bound) & (data[column] <= upper_bound)]
    return data

# Upon analysis in the previous code section, these are the features with outliers to be removed
columns_to_clean = ['trtbps', 'chol', 'fbs', 'thalachh', 'oldpeak', 'caa', 'thall']


cleaned_data = remove_outliers(data, columns_to_clean)

# To show the reduction in dataset size after outlier processing
print("Original Shape:", data.shape)
print("Cleaned Shape:", cleaned_data.shape)

In [28]:
accuracy_before_tuning = 0.7377
accuracy_after_tuning = 0.7869

models = ['Before Tuning', 'After Tuning']

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.bar(models, [accuracy_before_tuning, accuracy_after_tuning], color=['skyblue', 'orange'])
plt.ylim(0, 1)
plt.title('Decision Tree Accuracy Before and After Tuning', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Accuracy', fontsize=12)
plt.xlabel('Model', fontsize=12)
plt.text(0, accuracy_before_tuning + 0.02, f'{accuracy_before_tuning*100:.2f}%', ha='center', fontsize=10)
plt.text(1, accuracy_after_tuning + 0.02, f'{accuracy_after_tuning*100:.2f}%', ha='center', fontsize=10)

plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

By adding the parameter max_depth, the accuracy of the model has improved by 4.83% The parameter max_depth controls the maximum number of splits a tree can make and is used to prevent overfitting. A deeper tree can fit training data better and produce better accuracy results.
